  "descriptions": [
    {
      "descrType": "Overview",
      "description": "The 9M96 is a medium-range, agile surface-to-air missile developed by Russia's Fakel design bureau for integration with both S-300 (PMU variants) and S-400 air defense systems. Introduced in 2005, the 9M96 provides short- to medium-range air defense against aircraft, helicopters, cruise missiles, and tactical ballistic missiles. A unique feature is quad-packing—four missiles can be loaded into a single launch tube, allowing a single TEL to carry up to 16 missiles (four tubes × four missiles). The missile employs active radar homing and gas-dynamic lateral thrusters for high maneuverability in the endgame phase.",
      "shortDescription": "Agile medium-range SAM with active radar homing and gas-dynamic control; quad-packable.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Design",
      "description": "The 9M96 features a compact, streamlined airframe optimized for packaging density and agility. Propulsion is provided by a solid-fuel rocket motor enabling high acceleration and sustained supersonic cruise. The unique gas-dynamic control system employs lateral thrusters to achieve extreme maneuverability in the terminal phase, enabling engagement of highly maneuverable targets and defense against evasive tactics. Guidance is active radar homing in terminal phase, with datalink updates during the cruise phase. The warhead is a pre-fragmented anti-aircraft type. The compact size permits four missiles to be contained and launched from a single tube, significantly increasing the defensive firepower of individual launch platforms without increasing platform dimensions.",
      "shortDescription": "Compact agile SAM with active radar homing and gas-dynamic control; four-per-tube launcher configuration.",
      "classification": "U"
    }
  ],
